Racial Discrimination
Over the last few years, concerns about police brutality, racial oppression, and marginalization have dominated the American news, in part because of a new generation of activists who demand that such practices come to an end. These are very complex issues that are made up of many different sides and perspectives, but in the context of American history, they are anything but new.
When it comes to things like racial inequality or oppression, what we're fundamentally talking about is racial discrimination . This is the practice of treating someone differently (and usually badly) because of the color of their skin. For example, during the first half of the 20th century, African American children were sent to separate schools that were often underfunded and lacked resources. This was an act of racial discrimination because the reason for the separation was the color of their skin.
Racial discrimination has been an unfortunate part of American history since Europeans began establishing colonies in the early 17th century. This is an incredibly complicated subject that is too difficult to explain within the confines of a single lesson. Nevertheless, there are certain factors that contribute to racial discrimination, and by exploring them, you'll hopefully gain some insight into how and why the practice occurs.
