Racism and Self-Esteem
One of the most common things that lead one person to discriminate against another is self-esteem, which are the feelings that we have about our abilities or value. During the 17th and 18th centuries, for example, the colonists believed themselves superior to the Native populations around them, which they used to justify imprisoning the Native Americans or taking their land away.
The colonists operated on a doctrine of white superiority, believing that because they were white and supposedly more 'civilized' than Native peoples, they deserved better treatment and resources. In a broader context, this behavior is known as positive distinctiveness, when one group strives to be better than other groups. While it is often used to justify discrimination, it's actually one of the more common ways that we establish our identities and sense of belonging in the world. Like when fans of sports teams have rivalries with the fans of other sports teams, they are usually not being discriminatory but creating a positive self-concept.
Scientific Racism
Through the 17th, 18th, and 19th centuries, feelings of white superiority were commonly used to justify the poor or unequal treatment of people from racially minoritized backgrounds, but many people believed their behavior to be rooted in science. This theory, known as scientific racism, used pseudo-scientific perspectives to provide empirical evidence that white people were superior to people of other races. For instance, the difference in facial features like a larger nose or variations in cranial structure were believed to be a sign that non-white people were of lower intelligence or generally inferior. This has since been disproved.
Stereotypes and Control
The previous examples have explored racial discrimination in a historical context, but that doesn't mean that the practice has become less common. Unfortunately, the feelings of superiority and pseudo-scientific theories from the past have had a profound influence on the prevalence of racial discrimination in the present.
Many acts of modern discrimination are the result of stereotypes, which are beliefs about a person or group that are very simple and often inaccurate. For example, the stereotype that young African American men are more violent or more likely to commit crimes has led to an increased fear among the broader public and discrimination by law enforcement.
